INSERT INTO `jos_jf_content` VALUES(150, 2, 204, 'content', 'title', 'COMBATING ILL-TREATMENT AND IMPUNITY AND EFFECTIVE INVESTIGATION OF ILL-TREATMENT IN THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA', 'c39683579e41b295567de311e737f0af', '', '2011-03-18 06:21:19', 64, 1);
INSERT INTO `jos_jf_content` VALUES(151, 2, 204, 'content', 'alias', 'combating-ill-treatment-and-impunity-and-effective-investigation-of-ill-treatment-in-the-republic-of-armenia', 'efa80d10f251038bcee5e8287cb42609', '', '2011-03-18 06:21:19', 64, 1);
INSERT INTO `jos_jf_content` VALUES(152, 2, 204, 'content', 'introtext', '<p align="justify"><img src="images/stories/x1.jpg" border="0" hspace="10" vspace="10" align="right" />On 16-th of March Council of Europe and the Association of Judges of the RA organized a round table for judges of the Republic of Armenia “On combating ill-treatment and impunity and effective investigation of ill-treatment”. Long-term consultant of CoE arrived to Yerevan in order to meet judges, law-enforcement Agencies and to discuss legislation of the Republic of Armenia, judicial practice and its issues relating to ill-treatment. <br />The round table also participated Representatives of Public Prosecutor’s Office of the RA, Special Investigative Service of the RA, Police of the RA, Staff of Ombudsman Office of the RA and International Organizations.<br />Chairman of the Criminal Chamber of the Cassation Court of the RA <strong>Davit AVETISYAN</strong> greeted everyone and noted that the issue available not only in our country, but also in other various countries, which has more improved legislative system. An issue concerning combating ill-treatment and impunity is solved by the Constitution of the RA and by International obligations undertaken by the Republic of Armenia. Certainly, availability of legislative norms is another issue, and its practical functioning is another. This issue is very actual for our country, and that’s why Courts of the RA, particularly the Cassation Court of the RA makes additional efforts to ensure combating ill-treatment and impunity.</p>', 'a7a9cb6d508cc0886baae1624960ed21', '', '2011-03-18 06:21:19', 64, 1);
INSERT INTO `jos_jf_content` VALUES(153, 2, 204, 'content', 'fulltext', '<p><img src="images/stories/x2.jpg" border="0" hspace="10" vspace="10" align="left" />During last two years Cassation Court of the RA made a number of case-law decisions. In 2009 a judgment concerning a case of G. Mikaelyan related to a right of freedom and personal inviolability, but with many issues related to the ill-treatment and the fight against impunity. Practice shows that people subject to ill-treatment and torture, especially during the 3 hours, when a person has only a status of a person who was brought to Police and unfortunately, our legislation does not give the answer to the issue of what rights he has. In order to solve this issue in 2009 on the decision of Gagik Mikaelian the Cassation Court of the RA established that at this stage a person is factually considered deprived of his liberty, and he must have certain rights to know why he was brought to body of criminal proceedings, has he a right to a lawyer, one call right /opportunity to say his location to the relatives/. This decision of the Cassation Court of the RA established the status and rights of person, who was brought to the Police. <br />The legislation of the RA still has no regulation on the period of body of pre-trial proceedings shall be obliged to present the arrest protocol, and that’s the reason  why presentation of  arrest protocol often delays during pre-trial proceedings and investigation continues without the participation of the defender. <br />To fill the omission in the legislation the Cassation Court of the RA established that the arrest protocol should be given to a person immediately, if it is not possible, then in 1 hour.<br />The Cassation Court of the RA also made a number of other decisions made that directly relate to ill-treatment and the fight against impunity, particularly in 2010 by the decision of the case of Araik Gzoyan the Cassation Court established that if the Court has statement on torture, it must apply to petition the prosecutor''s office to start a criminal case.<br />The Investigation body should be independent, guided by UN Convention Article 4 on combating torture and other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment and punishment, according to which: “Each Contracting State shall ensure that all actions of torture in accordance with the criminal legislation should be examined as crime. The same applies to attempts to subject to torture, as well as actions of each person, who takes part in it”.<br />Frequently citizens, who have subjected to torture, do not apply to relevant authorities, because they think if they bring a complaint against the investigator, it must examine the same body or the superior officer of him, in this case, it becomes meaningless, and the applicant can not have any expectation.  <br />Long-term consultant of CoE Mr. <strong>Eric Svanidze</strong> noted the legislative field of prohibition against ill-treatment, fundamental legal guarantees which include the following rights: 1. To inform arrested person''s relative or a third person by his choice about his arrest, 2. The right to have a lawyer, which should include a scheme ensuring of effective legal aid insolvent persons, confidential meetings with a lawyer and a right to questioning in his presence, 3. right to access to a doctor, which, should include a right to be examined by the doctor invited by arrested person''s choice and by forensic doctors, all medical examinations should be implemented in the police and non-medical personnel without hearing, and if the doctor does not require the directly opposite, the results must be properly recorded and be accessible to the arrested person and lawyer, 4. The fact of arrest should be properly, fully and clearly recorded and that record should be accessible to the arrested person and a lawyer, 5. The arrested person should be clearly informed in language which he understands of his rights and he should be granted a document which directly assigns these rights, arrested persons must be put their signature, which verifies, that they are informed of their rights.<img src="images/stories/x3.jpg" border="0" hspace="10" vspace="10" align="right" /><br />These rights must be implemented in the first moment of deprivation of liberty. Even short-term delays to provide a doctor or a lawyer or unreasonable long delays to inform about the arrest can not correspond to these requirements.<br />Mr. <strong>E. Svanidze</strong> also mentioned the main factors of the fight against ill treatment, by giving special place to statistical data, and demanded that consistent scheme of results of police activity and corresponding methods of preparation of statistical data on the level of criminality should be submitted to the public in order to prevent the level of crime of individual officers of the Police as well as the whole system and the public.<br />The Executive Director of the Association of Judges of the RA, PhD in Law, Professor of YSU, Senior Scientist of NAS RA <strong>Vahe Yengibaryan</strong> and Senior Assistant of the Chairman of Criminal Chamber of the Cassation Court of the RA, PhD student <strong>Anna Vardapetyan</strong> also made reports on prohibition of ill-treatment and torture by presenting in detail the practice of the Cassation Court of the RA on the issue. </p><p align="right"><strong>Amalya HARUTYUNYAN</strong></p>', '9f75340605714ba40c7af12ecf6f6cb6', '', '2011-03-18 06:21:19', 64, 1);
